Keyword Naming Conventions
----------------------------------------------------------

   All names referencing values in this IK file start with the characters `INS' followed by the NAIF Chandrayaan-2 Orbiter spacecraft ID number(-152) followed by a NAIF three digit ID code for instrument. 
   
   The remainder of the keyword name is an underscore character followed by the unique name of the data item. For example, the OHRC PAN boresight direction in the OHRC frame is specified by:

         INS-152270_BORESIGHT

   The upper bound on the length of the name of any data item is 32 characters.

   If the same item is included in more than one file, or if the same item appears more than once within a single file, the latest value supersedes any earlier values.


Instrument Overview
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
OHRC used to image the moon surface with high spatial resolution. OHRC images used
to characterize the landing site (as its primary goal) with a ground sampling of 0.25-
0.32 m. This data is used to identify and characterize the landing area before the
landing of Lander. OHRC images used to identify the major hazards of importance like
slopes, boulders, craters and shadows. Based on these observations, the landing path
(trajectory) is planned. Currently OHRC is used for imaging scientific regions of interest
(as its secondary goal) and identification and characterization of future landing sites.
This camera is based on reflective system with large aperture of about 300 mm
and 12K TDI detector. The camera generates monochrome images with ground
sampling of 0.25 m from 100 km altitude and swath of about 3 km at nadir. 
With 0.25m GSD from 100km altitude, dwell time is around 160Î¼sec and very low
photon signal has to be detected by OHRC with SNR requirement of greater than 50.
Time Delay Integration (TDI) based imaging sensor has an advantage over external
frame addition technique in terms of read noise components. 


